{"id":"2303.05979","submitter":"Marcel Guardia","authors":"Andrew Clarke, Jacques Fejoz, Marcel Guardia","title":"A counterexample to the theorem of Laplace-Lagrange on the stability of\n  semimajor axes","comments":"arXiv admin note: text overlap with arXiv:2210.11311","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.DS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A longstanding belief has been that the semimajor axes, in the Newtonian\nplanetary problem, are stable. In the course of the XIX century, Laplace,\nLagrange and others gave stronger and stronger arguments in this direction,\nthus culminating in what has commonly been referred to as the first\nLaplace-Lagrange stability theorem. In the problem with 3 planets, we prove the\nexistence of orbits along which the semimajor axis of the outer planet\nundergoes large random variations thus disproving the theorem of\nLaplace-Lagrange. The time of instability varies as a negative power of the\nmasses of the planets. The orbits we have found fall outside the scope of the\ntheory of Nekhoroshev-Niederman because they are not confined by the\nconservation of angular momentum and because the Hamiltonian is not (uniformly)\nconvex with respect to the Keplerian actions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 10 Mar 2023 15:21:19 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-03-13"}
